data.content:
Here's what happened:

**C# 14 span overload resolution changed which `.Contains()` gets called.**

In .NET 9, `array.Contains(num)` resolved to `Enumerable.Contains<T>()`. In C# 14 / .NET 10, new built-in span conversions cause it to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is **not representable in a LINQ expression tree**, the compiled expression throws at runtime.

**Fix — force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`:**

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast the array to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these disambiguates the overload back to the expression-tree-compatible `Enumerable.Contains`.
